Friday, January 1, 1954

I begin 1954 with the following status of the rattlesnake book
Chapter 3 Paleontology (unrevised)
Chapter 8 Reproduction (unrevised)
Chapter 5-6 About 70% revision is complete. Populations and their ecology.
Chapter 7 Revision complete, but requires copying.

Cleared up a lot of miscellaneous work today. Not much lost time. Made the corrections in Chapter 7 lately suggested by Perkins and Shaw. Read back a part of this section lately copied, but didn't finish this.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:30 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Saturday, January 2, 1954

A lot of miscellaneous work cleared up today. Went over a part of Chapter 7 with Perkins. Not a particularly profitable day.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:31 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Sunday, January 3, 1954

Made a start again today on altitudes and other parts of Chapter 6 and made good progress. Decided to treat altitudes separately only in the case of the the highest species -- horridus, viridis, triseriatus -- in their respective areas. Other altitude remarks will be included in the appropriate sections given over to habitat preferences, treated by species.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/07/2012 11:03 AM
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:34 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Monday, January 4, 1954

At the office for a couple of hours this morning; then came home and worked on the rattler book until 9:30 PM. The first day of the regime. Worked on altitudes and their incorporation in the habitat write-ups. Made rather good progress.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:36 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Tuesday, January 5, 1954

At the office for a couple of hours. Had a talk with Dr. Schroeder about the progress and present status of the rattler book. Was authorized by him to hire someone on an hourly basis to do the copy work; also to make changes in the diagrams. Left with him some recent correspondence with the University of California Press.

Spent most of the afternoon at a movie, and the evening repairing a lamp.

Wednesday, January 6, 1954

At the office most of the morning; worked on habitats in the afternoon and evening, making good progress.

Thursday, January 1, 1954

Concluded negotiations with Miss Molloy to take over the miscellaneous copy work at $1.50 per hour. This was satisfactory to Schroeder.

Friday, January 8, 1954

Library Commission meeting took most of the morning.

Received from Littell a letter and 4 unrevised sections of the manuscript.

Got started again incorporating altitudes in Chapter 6.

Television antenna put up today.

Read back with corrections the temporal activity and limitations part of Chapter 7 from Perkins.

A lot of miscellaneous work done today, including a meeting of the board of the Natural History Society in the afternoon. Reviewed a paper on the Scute-Oreganus hybrids for Sherburne Cook Jr., and corrected proofs of a hobby pages for The Rotarian.

Friday, January 15, 1954

Made a good attack on dens and population, incorporating the new material including that of Stephen Harwig of Pittsburgh.

Saturday, January 16, 1954

Today received the following very gratifying and encouraging telegram from Littell of U.C. Press.

COMMITTEE ACCEPTED MANUSCRIPT AS IS. ONLY PROBLEMS REMAINING ARE ESTIMATES, ILLUSTRATIONS, AND ORGANIZATION. CONGRATULATIONS AND WE ARE ALL VERY HAPPY ABOUT IT.

Worked on revising population section today and made good progress. Begin to see daylight in this Chapter 5-6 combination at last, a very troublesome bit of work.

Scholia Club tonight.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/07/2012 11:44 AM
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:50 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Sunday, January 17, 1954

Today finished the combination Chapters 5 and 6. Populations and Habitats. will require careful reading back that will take some time.

Expect now to delay starting the revision of another section until I catch up on all kinds of miscellaneous work, some herpetological and some not. Another conference with Littell is advisable before going further with the revisionary work.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:52 PM

Monday, January 18, 1954

Spent half a day at the office; the rest at home writing letters. This is going to be quite a chore.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 04:53 PM

Tuesday, January 19, 1954

Attended a Solar director's meeting that took all morning and a meeting of the San Diego Scientific Library that took much of the afternoon. Nothing else done today.

Page Edit History:

Wednesday, January 20, 1954

Started for San Francisco on the 7:45 AM train. At the L.A. Public Library from 11 until 12 and from 2:45 to 4:00. Picked up a few items but nothing important.

At noon (12-2:30) attended a lunch at the Statler. Heard a talk by Dr. Vannebar Bush on science progress.

Caught the Lark to San Francisco.

Page Edit History:

Thursday, January 21, 1954

Spent the day from 10 to 5 with Emlon Littell and J.B. Goetz of the U.C. Press. Many details of the proposed publication were worked out. then went out to Wormeser's.

Page Edit History:

Friday, January 22, 1954

Called on the Chikerings from 9 to 9:30. Then went to a meeting of the Californian State Chamber of Commerce. Heard a talk by Gov. Goodwin Knight at lunch. Went to U.C. at 2:15. Saw Stebbins and then worked in the U.C. Library from 4 to 6:30. Cleaned up a few items.

Caught the Lark homeward.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/07/2012 01:06 PM

Saturday, January 23, 1954

Arrived in San Diego at 12:30 and went at once to a meeting of the Zoo Board that lasted until 3:15. Explained the latest developments with the UC Press regarding the publication of the rattlesnake book and did it very badly.

A little catch up work in the afternoon. Out late to dinner with the Forward crowd at their home.

Thursday, January 28, 1954

Worked all day on this and that; particularly on checking the copy work that Miss Molloy has recently done. This took a lot of time.

Also picked up an important reference at the SD Medical Library.

Littell called this afternoon from La Jolla. He said the estimates were not ready yet but would be sent soon. He said the manuscript had been favorably commented on in Berkely because it was so "understanding."

Out to dinner tonight.

At 3:30 took the kids to the Living Desert movie. very good, but the Chionactis wasn't natural.

At the office a short time only.

Hip bothering me.

Sunday.. February 14, 1954

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 05:56 PM

Monday, February 15, 1954

Morning at the office.

Spent the afternoon overhauling the loose-leaf books containing the rattler records. A long job that should have been done long ago.

In the evening gave a talk on rattlers to a group of patients in a tubercular word of the Naval Hospital.

A new myth: To make friends with a snake show it the back of your hand first; if you show it the palm the sweat will anger it.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/10/2012 01:13 PM
  • janetmary 08/27/2012 06:01 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Tuesday, February 16, 1954

Library Commission meeting with City Manager Campbell from 2 to 4:30 at my home. At the office this morning from 10:30 until noon. Except this worked from 8 until 11 PM rearranging and expanding all the loose-leaf books in the hall including rattler and collection records. Made good progress on a tedious but necessary job.

The above is the entry for Wednesday the 17th.

Tuesday met with Miss Breed to discuss library business. Went to the office for a couple of hours. Rest of the time worked on the loose-leaf record system.

Thursday, February 18, 1954

Attended a meeting at 7:45 of the Armed Services Committee of the San Diego Chamber of Commerce. Then worked on the Company's Annual report in the office. In the afternoon completed the renovation of the 3 hole loose-leaf book filing system.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/10/2012 01:18 PM

Friday, February 19, 1954

Went to the office in the morning and worked on the annual report. At noon made an atomic energy talk to the San Diego Bar Association and their wives. Littell came in this afternoon and we discussed many details of the book publishing program. The Press people seemed to be agreed that a 2-volume format is desirable.

Too tired tonight to do anything which might be deemed constructive. Talks such as that at noon today are particularly tiring at my age.

Various work today, including making special scale counts on the specimens of omiltemanus that have accumulated.

Scholin tonight.

Thursday, February 25, 1954

At the office for an hour or so in the morning.

Went to the zoo and got Perkins - Shaw suggestions for the first half of Chapter 6 Habitats. then made suitable corrections in original.

Got from Miss Molloy the new copy of the second half. Started to make a check of this.

Out to dinner and a philharmonic concert tonight.

Friday, February 26, 1954

Saturday, February 27, 1954

In the morning worked on checking Chapter 6 part 2 recently completed by Miss Molloy.

Then a meeting of the Zoo publication committee from 11:30 to 12:30 and of the Board from 12:30 to 3:30. They decided, with reference to the rattler book on 3000 copies, 15.00 selling price, and 2 volumes. Also a fairly liberal estimate on cuts and additions.

Met Johnson of Sacramento.

Spent the rest of the day and evening correcting Chapter 6 as copied.

Sunday, February 28, 1954

Spent the morning finishing the checking of Chapter 6 and some miscellaneous work.

Made a real start in the afternoon on the revision of Chapter 8 Reproduction and made some real progress.

Out to dinner at Price's tonight.

Saturday, April 24, 1954

Met Allen Chickering at Glendale S.P. station at 8:40 AM. Went to the Santa Ana Botanic Garden and spent 2 hours viewing the building and planting.

Then went to Banner queen Ranch via Corona (where we had lunch at the Hickory Barbeque), Elsinore, Temecula, Warner's Ranch, and San Felipe Valley. It was cool and breezy.

1 gopher L DOR Albennill, Riv. Co. grass
1 golpher S DOR Elsinore Riv. Co, grass
1 red racer M DOR upper end of San Felipe Valley (7 miles north of Scissor's Crossing) Grass black on neck with good light cross rings. After leaving our baggage at Banner queen we returned to Scissors Crossing and then went south to Vallecitos State Station and Aqua Caliente Spring.

1 Red racer DOR M. 5 miles south of Scissors Crossing. Then arid grass.

Returned to Banner Queen, arriving at 6:10. It was cold and windy; no purpose in going out on the road. Very windy all night. Not a live snake or lizard seen today. Miles today 225.

Tuesday, June 1, 1954

Spent the entire day (9-4:30) with Littell, Goetz, and Swanson discussing various phases of the rattler book. I made many notes of the decisions reached, later incorporated in a typewritten memo. Swanson who had edited (and then returned) the Introduction, and Chapters 1, 6, and 7 had made a long typewritten report or comments, which Littell was somewhat embarassed to keep me from seeing, so it have been rather adverse. Our discussions however were quite amicable and settled many doubtful points of context and arrangement. Swanson left before noon and we went to lunch at the Faculty Club.

That evening I looked over some of Swanson's editing and was considerably disturbed to find the large number of changes he had recommended that did not involve the correction of errors and/or observations.

Sunday, October 10, 1954

Today is a sort of a milestone for I finished the section on phylogeny (including a preliminary draft of the diagram) and this is the last of the unwritten parts of the rattler book. So it is finished after 9 1/2 years. Of course there is much still to do, corrections, minor additions, and a lot of editorial work in co-operation with Littell, Swenson, and The Press. but as of today it's a completely finished book.

Wednesday, November 10, 1954

Had a couple of conferences this morning on the rate case at the office; then caught the 11:45 for Los Angeles and attended a meeting of the Board of Founders Insurance Co. Miscellaneous work in the evening, having returned on the 5 PM train.

Thursday, November 11, 1954

At the meeting of the Library Commission 9-12.

Went to lunch with Chuck Shaw and Joe Slevin.

Miscellaneous work in the afternoon and early evening rechecking Chapter 5, rattle; and correcting the carbon copy of Chapter 17.

Then Brattstrom came in and we talked phylogeny and other matters for 1 1/2 hours.

Monday, November 15, 1954

Arrived at Oakland on time and went to the Shattuck Hotel. Called Littel and made arrangements to meet him at 1:15 PM. Went to the U.C. Library and worked until 11:30. Called on Stebbins at MVZ but he was out.

Went to the U.C. Press with Littell at 1:30. First called on Fru??? who told me that John Jennings would hereafter handle all matters having to do with my book hitherto handled by Littell. Littell was away too much. Design would handled by Mrs. Rita Carroll. We spent the rest of the afternoon discussing many aspects of the book - style, schedule, etc. Very profitable discussion.

Spent the evening rereading Chapter 6.

Page Edit History:
  • lkairy 06/05/2014 05:59 PM
  • janetmary 11/02/2012 05:26 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Tuesday, November 16, 1954

Conferred at the Press today from 9 AM to 4 PM. Swenson was there in the morning. For the first time sample printed pages were available for comment. The bibliography was discussed at length. Went to lunch with Littell and Mrs. Carroll.

The entire manuscript was available and the Press had the pages numbered serially. I think there were 4500.

Mrs. Carroll showed me her first sketches for the design of the book.

I returned to the hotel at 4 and wrote a memo of the 2 day conference.

Then started the rereading of Chapter 7.

Page Edit History:

Went over to San Francisco to a Light and Power council meeting. Then to the Stanford Medical Library.

Met Amy Jo at the Clift Hotel where we discussed the project of the chapter head figures.

Thursday, December 23, 1954

At the office in the morning; had a considerable discussion of rate-case matters.

Rest of the spare time worked on Chapter 13.

At a zoo board meeting 4:30 to 6. They authorized the officers to sign the contract with the UC Press. There are still a few bugs in it, but they are probably not worth fussing over.

Also I signed an assignment transferring all my rights in the book to the zoo.

This evening Rita Carroll called from San Francisco and told me of her recent estimates on the book, now 1538 pages. She said typesetting on Chapters 5 and 6 should begin on next Monday. We also discussed design briefly. There have been no important changes in the decisions to date.

Saturday, December 25, 1954

Lunch at the Millers today; then caught the 4 PM train for LA and Berkeley.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 11/02/2012 06:05 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Ryr\>

Arrived at Oakland an hour late. Kept a taxi waiting for 1/2 hour, while I changed return reservation from Friday night to Thursday night. Had to take a compartment to get anything. Later it proved to be fortunate that I had done so because of the heavy Holiday travel.

Called Amy Jo and Donnie upon arrival. Then worked in my room at the Silva Motel on Chapter 13 until 4 PM. Then went to 55 Fifth Ave. Found Allan sick in bed, and Laura Jean not much better.

Talked to A.H. about the vignettes.

Left at 9:30. Made unusually good connections and got back to the motel about 11.

_____________________________________________________________

Appointed to consider a change in the the by-laws to avoid the kind of protest that had been entered this year by Mayr et. al. He said however that this year's election would stand, so I president for 1955.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 11/02/2012 06:10 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Monday, December 27, 1954

Spent almost the entire day at the venom symposium. The attendance was small and disappointing. Met Pollard, Porges, Mrs. Buckley, Dr. Criley, Stahnke, Tinkham and many others. Most of the foreigners who had expected to come were not there; financial troubles, so it was said. However I did meet Fraenkel-Co???t, his brother-in-law Slotta, Goncalves, Trethewire from Australia and several others. Porges was a rather poor chairman.

Had a sandwich lunch with Donnie and Brattstrom.

There were few present when my paper was read. Only one question was asked.

Some of the papers were good; some fair or too technical (biochemical) for me.

Borrowed Minton's paper and took it back to the motel for making notes.

In the evening went to an interesting lecture on South Africa by Cowles. Very depressing as to the future. Met Stunkard of the SSZ Society who said that a committee was to be appointed to consider a change in the the by-laws to avoid the kind of protest that had been entered this year by Mayr et. al. He said however that this year's election would stand, so I president for 1955.

Notes:

janetmary

So many names. Not sure which to index

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 11/02/2012 06:16 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Tuesday, December 28, 1954

Donnie called for me at 8:45, a great convenience.

First went to the venom symposium and heard several papers; then to the SSZ meeting where I heard Re??m?? on Taricha, Savage on Xantusia (he had named a genus Klauberiana after me -- had not previously known this) and Brattstrom on Crotalid phylogeny based on osteology. Then took lunch with Stebbins and his uncle; then to the Biology Library for a few items; and finally to the meeting of the Herpetology League for a battle between Stahnke and Shannon as to the desirability of using cryotherapy. This was quite bitter and personal. Then back to the venom meetings.

Donnie took me down to the motel.

Had expected to go out to dinner at Fisherman's Wharf in San Francisco but through a mix up I failed to arrange transportation and so stayed home.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 11/02/2012 06:22 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Wednesday, December 29, 1954

Donnie called for me as usual at 9:45. Jack Heyneman was along. First called on John Jennings at the U.C. Press and talked over a variety of matters. They expect to have a publication schedule available shortly.

Spent the rest of the day at the venom symposium. Usual small attendance. Some papers good; some uninteresting.

In the evening went first to the Herpetology League dinner. Saw Camp and Miss Attatt. Woodbury presided. Slevin talked on Galapagos iguanas.

Then went to a Western Society of Naturalist meeting where Hubbs made a fine talk on hybridization of fish.

Chuck Shaw drove me home at 9:30.

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 11/02/2012 06:27 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:58 PM

Thursday, December 30, 1954

Was at the venom sessions all day. The Shannon-Stahnke battle was renewed. It was very dreary the second time around.

The paper on available antiviruses listed a lot I had never heard of. Mrs. Buckley promised to send me the list upon her return.

The panel discussion was fair and was recorded. I talked on the taxonomy of the South American rattlers; also on the need for ????? the North American crotalic ??? at atroc. Criley said they were doing this.

Slotta told me things were tough in Brazil because of politics and personalities. He would like to get a job up here. They think it will be worse than ever at the Institute Butantan with do Amarel in charge. He sounded very discouraged. He was hard to understand because of a strong accent.

It was a pretty good day.

Took a taxi to the 1st and Broadway station in Oakland and had dinner with Bow??? Bello.

Notes:

janetmary

Some words I can't read. Look for ????

Page Edit History:
  • janetmary 11/05/2012 11:54 AM

Friday, December 31, 1954

Arrived at San Diego at noon through the help of a red cap that got me through the line. I think many people were left. GG not at the station but found her there when I went back in the taxi to pick up my hat and coat, which I had forgotten.

Spent most of the afternoon at the office catching up.

At a New Years party at Cavenee's in the evening.
